lass="RatingStar__backgroundFill" d="M12.4770229,1.34326985 L15.0891563,9.1315756 L23.4968842,9.1315756 C23.7747474,9.1315756 24,9.35682823 24,9.63469143 C24,9.79809886 23.9206399,9.95132779 23.7871766,10.0456121 L16.9959586,14.8432273 L19.5982827,22.6117477 C19.6865419,22.8752212 19.5445026,23.1603569 19.2810291,23.2486161 C19.1293386,23.2994298 18.9625235,23.2750752 18.8316924,23.1830139 L12.0000207,18.3758025 L5.1685337,23.1876292 C4.94136559,23.3476374 4.62749722,23.2931935 4.46748907,23.0660254 C4.37533831,22.9351963 4.35092131,22.7683321 4.4017231,22.616585 L7.00408269,14.8432273 L0.212864685,10.0456121 C-0.0140805533,9.88528803 -0.0680876559,9.57134421 0.0922364448,9.34439897 C0.186520784,9.21093568 0.339749724,9.1315756 0.503157148,9.1315756 L8.910885,9.1315756 L11.5230185,1.34326985 C11.6113744,1.0798288 11.8965622,0.937894292 12.1600033,1.02625024 C12.3095218,1.07639751 12.4268756,1.19375135 12.4770229,1.34326985 Z"></path></g></svg></span></span></div><span class="Text Text__body3"><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2061071677">August 23, 2019</a></span></section><section class="ReviewText"><section class="ReviewText__content"><div class="TruncatedText"><div class="TruncatedText__text TruncatedText__text--5" data-testid="contentContainer"><div><span class="Formatted">Don't read many Japanese books these days, one or two a year at best. As it's been a good while since I last ventured far East through literature I decided to try a Japanese writer I hadn't read before, rather than go back to the likes of Mishima, Kawabata or Tanizaki. I had a good idea how this novel was going to read, and was precisely right: a simple and beautiful prose touched with an echoing sadness. It was also somewhat nihilist in my eye, something that I wasn't expecting, but reading up on Dazai after, it no longer comes as a surprise, as he draws heavily on his own experiences in the novel. The Setting Sun deals with the decline of Japan’s aristocracy in the wake of World War II, and portrays characters adrift in a world that no longer feels familiar. The narrator, Kazuko, who is in her late twenties comes from a once-rich family whose fortunes have dried out. Having to part with their luxurious Tokyo home, she and her ailing mother move to a villa in a mountainous region to the west. But the harmony of their now fragile existence is unsettled by the return of Kazuko’s brother Naoji, a former opium addict, who again takes up the drug, after returning from action during the war. With a mother who's health is deteriorating, and Kazuko who goes about the novel either in tears or is on the verge of crying, the selfish and destructive Naoji squanders what money the family have left on binge drinking trips to Tokyo. Kazuko in the end tries to stabilize her life by foisting her affections on one of his so-called friends, an alcoholic novelist, eventually leading to a poignant finale that closed the story in a life affirming manner. Dazai writes with a subtle nature, and draws on the emotional complexities and actions of Kazuko giving the simple narrative a deeper feel. I can't say that I found Dazai in any way better or different from the likes of Kawabata, nor is the novel likely to resonate strong in the hours or days ahead, but it was nice to return to Japanese literature to freshen things up a bit, and I will certainly consider reading Dazai again. 3.5/5 <br /> <br /> </span></div></div></div></section></section><section class="ReviewCard__tags"><ul class="CollapsableList"><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/list/26706841?shelf=fiction" class="Button Button--tag-inline Button--small"><span class="Button__labelItem">fiction</span></a> <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/list/26706841?shelf=japan" class="Button Button--tag-inline Button--small"><span class="Button__labelItem">japan</span></a></ul></section><footer class="SocialFooter"><div data-testid="stats" class="SocialFooter__statsContainer"><div class="Button__container"